}\par\pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-480\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex81\expndtw1\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs45 After Ten Minutes Company L}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qc\li509\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-480\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex81\expndtw3\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs45 Veteran Fighters-Corporal \b Joe Time?}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qc\li538\fi0\ri0\sb14\sa0\sl-480\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex81\expndtw15\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs45 Tens of Soldier Life in}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qc\li514\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-480\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex81\expndtw2\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs45 Cuba.}\par \sect\sectd \sbknone\pgwsxn10170\pghsxn31680\marglsxn1569\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li24\fi0\ri0\sb629\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b\i0\cf1\charscalex81\expndtw7\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 DIRECT      \b0 NEWS      \b PROM       SANTIAGO.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li53\fi322\ri302\sb48\sa0\sl-370\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw3\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs40 Many home friends of the boys at the \expndtw9 front were gladened yesterday by the \expndtw3 receipt of letters.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li67\fi298\ri302\sb0\sa0\sl-370\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw4\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs40 Most of the epistles indicate that paper \expndtw6 is a scarce article fat Santiago.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li72\fi283\ri298\sb0\sa0\sl-370\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-1\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs40 A letter from Stewart Zyrd, received by \expndtw8 his sister, was written on an Arbuckle \expndtw-2 coffee label. One from Joe Shepard to \b his \b0\expndtw4 mother was written on the back of a let\-\expndtw-1 ter received from home and sent in an \expndtw-7 envelope*1ferned inside out.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li403\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-370\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw7\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs40 Both write in cheerful vein.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li96\fi307\ri298\sb0\sa0\sl-370\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-5\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs40 John Thoney has received the following \expndtw-2 letter from his son, Corporal Joe Thoney, \expndtw4 now in Cuba with Company L.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li91\fi322\ri302\sb10\sa0\sl-370\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw3\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs40 The letter is dated at Santiago July 11 \expndtw1 and reads as follows:}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qc\li29\fi0\ri0\sb192\sa0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw23\loch\af9\hich\af9\dbch\f10\cchs0\lang1033\fs18 \'95\'97}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li130\fi317\ri259\sb5\sa0\sl-346\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw13\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs38 "We are Well located here about two \expndtw20 miles from Santiago. If you were here \expndtw8 you could hear them bombarding the city.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li139\fi326\ri221\sb0\sa0\sl-346\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw17\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs38 "We' left Camp Alger June 22 and \expndtw13 marched to Dunn Luring, where we took \expndtw12 a train for Alexandria, Va., and boarded the steamer Norfolk, and steamed down \expndtw8 the Potomac to Old Point Comfort,where we rested and visited the many historic \expndtw14 points of interest around the fort.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li206\fi331\ri216\sb0\sa0\sl-346\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw20\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs38 "We boarded the Tale June 23 and \expndtw15 started oh our present trip to Santiago. \expndtw10 The trip was void of anything of interest.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li216\fi326\ri202\sb0\sa0\sl-346\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw9\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs38 "I took care of a sick man on the way \expndtw13 down and got a chance to get something \expndtw15 to eat. The boys could not get anything \expndtw24 for days at a time. The treatment on \expndtw9 board the boat was rotten.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li240\fi317\ri182\sb0\sa0\sl-350\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw11\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs38 "We finally landed at a place called \expndtw5 Siboney on June 27, and I had the 'pleas\-\expndtw17 ure' of being corporal of the guard the first night on Cuban soil. I was a bit \expndtw18 nervous but kept up courage and came \expndtw15 out all O. K.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li264\fi317\ri168\sb0\sa0\sl-355\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw9\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs38 "We moved a dozen times in a week \expndtw17 waiting for the rest of our brigade. It is \expndtw7 a lucky thing for us that all our regiment \expndtw20 was not landed at once. If it had been \expndtw4 our whole company would not be alive to \expndtw11 tell the tale.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li293\fi322\ri163\sb0\sa0\sl-350\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw11\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs38 "The balance of our regiment arrived \expndtw24 July 2, and we moved to the front at \expndtw8 once, leaving at 10 o'clock at night, ar\-\expndtw9 riving at the firing line next morning af\-\expndtw11 ter a continuous march all night.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qc\li34\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tlul\tx336\tlul\tx797 \f1\fs20{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs38 .{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li274\fi350\ri130\sb125\sa0\sl-331\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw4\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs38 "The trees were full of sharpshooters, \expndtw10 mostly all Frenchmen. They robbed the \expndtw19 dead of our uniforms and then had an \expndtw17 easy time picking off officers and red \expndtw3 cross men.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li264\fi326\ri144\sb0\sa0\sl-331\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 "They shot wounded men and red cross \expndtw3 men, using brass bullets, which is against \expndtw2 international law.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li254\fi326\ri139\sb0\sa0\sl-331\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw9\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 "They did not last long after our boys \expndtw13 got after them. We had orders to shoot \expndtw24 any man we saw up a tree. It was fan \expndtw5 to see the colored boys pick them out.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li269\fi317\ri120\sb0\sa0\sl-331\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw7\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 "While we laid down beside the hill \expndtw4 waiting for orders to go into the rifle pits \expndtw5 on top of the hill, two men who were ly\-\expndtw3 ing right by the side of me were shot, one \expndtw18 in the arm, and the other in the neck. \expndtw6 The latter died. The first had his arm \expndtw8 amputated on account of being shot with \expndtw7 a brass bullet.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li293\fi317\ri96\sb10\sa0\sl-331\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw15\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 "The bullets whizzed around us like \expndtw-2 flies, but we got used to them in about ten \expndtw9 minutes, and paid no attention to them, \expndtw10 Just like the vets.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li298\fi312\ri96\sb278\sa0\sl-326\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw8\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 "The Spaniards made a charge at 10 \expndtw3 o'clock at night to regain the hill that was \expndtw13 taken from them the day before In the \expndtw11 most gallant charge that was ever made \expndtw6 on a battlefield.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li336\fi298\ri67\sb19\sa0\sl-322\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-3\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 "The foreign officers who witnessed the \expndtw-1 charge say they do not see how our men \expndtw10 captured the hill, losing only 500 men \expndtw1 killed and wounded. The Spaniards must \expndtw9 have lost thousands. In the night charge \expndtw0 we had two men wounded, the Spaniards \expndtw-2 losing 840 killed and wounded. The_ fig\-\expndtw2 ures we received the next day from Hob-\expndtw6 son and his men.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li389\fi312\ri29\sb24\sa0\sl-322\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw10\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 "I tell you it did me good to see that brave lot of men when they passed our lines on their way to rejoin their ships.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li418\fi302\ri38\sb5\sa0\sl-322\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw11\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 "We rested at the hospital on our way \expndtw23 to the front. The sights would make \expndtw9 your blood run cold. Killed and wound\-\expndtw6 ed were strung out all along the line.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li418\fi317\ri24\sb14\sa0\sl-322\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw5\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 "We are guarding Shafter; head guards \expndtw10 at present. The regulars all threaten to \expndtw-2 leave the pits if we go in with Springfield \expndtw8 rifles. The smoke betrays our line and \expndtw12 makes us a good target for the enemy.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li418\fi322\ri0\sb5\sa0\sl-322\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw4\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 "You need have no fear for our safety. \expndtw2 We will have Santiago in a day or so. Do \expndtw8 not believe all of the newspaper reports \expndtw13 you see as most of them are all rot."}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li446\fi283\ri24\sb10\sa0\sl-322\slmult0 \f1\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw11\f1\cchs0\lang1033\fs39 The letter closes with the postscript, \expndtw8 "We are getting plenty to eat now."}\par }